## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



We created a framework that can be used to infer the status of the relationship between a main government agency and a range of different actors that are present in a consultation or dialogue process. The tool was designed to be used by outside observers who are in the meeting but do not participate, their job is to look at every interaction between the main agency that is hosting the consultation or dialogue process and the rest of actors and rank the interactions in two dimensions: 1) their predisposition to collaborate, and 2) their dialogue attitude. When the meeting ends, the information is systematized and put in the map, where the agency can visualize the relationship it has with all of the actors ranked from "excellent" to "in crisis". The tool's goal is to reflect back to government officials the status of relationships so that the can take more informed decisions as to where they need to focus energy in building, maintaining and fixing broken relationships.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



We found that government officials who organize consultation and dialogue processes are sometimes so focused on facilitating the session that they do not have the bandwidth to analyze some signals about the status of the relationship with different counterparts. Also, that it is not easy to order the relationships with the actors present in the session in a coherent way. This tool helps them to complement their own judgment on the status of relationships and make more informed decisions on what strategy to follow with each stakeholder in order to improve the relationship.
